8. Schema Manager
✓ DECISION: Schema Manager defines the data contract. Modal Editor defines presentation. These are independent governed artifacts.
✓ DECISION: Schema Manager covers two libraries in the prototype: Course Catalog and Credentials.
Course Patterns schema is architecturally defined but not built out in the prototype.
✓ DECISION: Supported field types:
TypeDescriptionVARCHAR(n)Short text with defined length limitTEXTLong text, no character limit (for descriptions, narratives)INTEGERWhole numbersDECIMALNumbers with decimal placesBOOLEANTRUE / FALSEDATEDate valuesENUMControlled vocabulary — allowed values defined in the schema
✓ DECISION: TEXT type was added specifically to support course descriptions.
255 characters (VARCHAR) is insufficient for full course descriptions. TEXT fields have no length limit enforced during bulk upload validation.
✓ DECISION: ENUM fields carry their allowed values directly in the schema definition.
The enumVals array is the source of truth for validation in bulk upload, for dropdowns in edit modals, and for enum reference rows in CSV templates.
✓ DECISION: course_subject is an ENUM field with 25 controlled values.
Values: English Language Arts, Mathematics, Science, Social Studies, Career & Technical Education, Fine Arts, Physical Education, World Language, Health, Journalism, Library Science, Drama/Theatre, Speech & Debate, Psychology, Philosophy, Economics, Government, Geography, Computer Science, Architecture, Agriculture, Business, Marketing, Finance, Hospitality.
✓ DECISION: All schema changes require Curriculum Director approval.
Operations: Add Field, Edit Field, Retire Field. All three generate approval queue entries. A retired field is marked deprecated (not deleted) for backward compatibility.
✓ DECISION: Pending schema fields remain visible in the schema list with a "Pending Approval" chip.
Approved fields move to Active. Rejected new fields are removed from the list; rejected edits revert to prior state; rejected retirements revert to Active.
✓ DECISION: The Schema Manager is the source of truth for bulk upload validation.
Required fields, VARCHAR length limits, ENUM allowed values, and type validation (DECIMAL must be numeric, BOOLEAN must be TRUE/FALSE/1/0/yes/no) are all derived from smSchemas at parse time — not hardcoded in the upload logic.

9. Bulk Upload
✓ DECISION: Bulk upload is a three-step modal flow: Upload → Preview & Validate → Confirm Import.
Step 1 — Upload:

Accepts CSV, XLSX, XLS
Drag-and-drop or file browser
Download Template button generates a schema-driven CSV with header row, sample data row, and enum reference comments
Template is always in sync with the active schema — no hardcoded column lists

Step 2 — Preview & Validate:

Preview table shows: Identifier, Name/Title, Type/Category, Issue count badge, Issue details
Summary tiles show Total Rows, Ready to Import, Warnings, Errors (blocked)
Filter pills: All rows / Warnings only / Errors only
Footer shows row counts dynamically

✓ DECISION: Errors block a row. Warnings import with a flag.
Validation RuleSeverityRequired field missingError (row skipped)VARCHAR value exceeds defined lengthError (row skipped)ENUM value not in allowed listWarning (imports, flagged)DECIMAL/INTEGER field contains non-numeric valueWarningBOOLEAN field has unexpected valueWarningTEXT fieldsNo length validation
✓ DECISION: Comment rows (lines starting with #) are ignored during parsing.
This allows enum reference comments in downloaded templates to be uploaded back without causing errors.
Step 3 — Confirm Import:

Import log lists every row with outcome
Imported records land in Course Catalog with status: 'pending' and isNew: true
Each imported course generates an approval card in Pending Approvals
Footer note reminds: "Records are now visible in Course Catalog — search for them there now"

✓ DECISION: Bulk upload Download Template uses the live schema.
Column headers, sample values, and enum reference comments all derive from smSchemas['catalog'] at runtime. Adding a field to the schema automatically adds it to the template.

10. Approval Workflow
✓ DECISION: All governed changes route through Pending Approvals before taking effect.
Governed change types: Schema field add/edit/retire, Course record add/edit (bulk or manual), Credential record add/edit.
✓ DECISION: Only the Curriculum Director role can approve or reject items.
Other roles (CTE SME, Labor Market SME, Math SME) can view the queue but Approve/Reject buttons are disabled. A role simulator dropdown is available for demo/testing.
✓ DECISION: Approval cards are grouped by library type.
Groups: Credentials, Course Catalog, Schema Changes. Each group shows a count.
✓ DECISION: Schema change cards carry a blue "Schema Change" badge to distinguish them visually from record changes.
✓ DECISION: Approving a course sets status: 'active' and writes a log entry.
Rejecting a new course removes it from ccCourses. Rejecting an edit reverts the record to its prior values.
✓ DECISION: Approving a credential applies any staged edits (_pendingEdits) and sets status: 'active'.
The CoV score and seal tier from the staged edits are applied at approval time.
✓ DECISION: Withdrawn and superseded approval items are excluded from the queue view.
Status values: pending, approved, rejected, withdrawn, superseded. Only pending items appear in the queue.
✓ DECISION: Resubmitting a pending record supersedes the prior approval card.
The old card gets status: 'superseded' and disappears from the queue. A fresh card is pushed with the updated content. No duplicate cards.

11. Course & Credential Edit Modals
✓ DECISION: Edit modals are slide-out drawers from the right edge, 520px wide.
They use a shared CSS pattern (.ce-tab, .ce-panel, .ce-toggle, .ce-flag-row, .ce-log-entry).
✓ DECISION: All modal panels use single-column vertical layout.
No horizontal grids inside modal panels. Fields stack vertically using sm-form-group with flex-direction: column on the panel container.
✓ DECISION: Every modal has a grounding field strip at the top of each tab.
Shows the record identifier (course code or credential ID) and name in a muted banner. Staff always know which record they are editing regardless of which tab they are on.
Course edit modal tabs:
TabContentsCoreCourse Code (read-only), Course Name, Category, Credit Hours, Course Subject (ENUM dropdown from schema), SCED Code, CTE Cluster, Course Description (TEXT), Reason for ChangeDiploma FlagsToggle switches for Core 40, AHD, THD, Core 40 with Technical Honors (2029)LogRead-only audit trail — date, actor, action, note
Credential edit modal tabs:
TabContentsCoreCredential ID (read-only), Credential Name, Short Name, Issuing Organization, Credential Type (ENUM dropdown), Career Cluster (ENUM dropdown), National Recognition (toggle), Reason for ChangeCoV ScoringEconomic Value input, Upskilling Value input, Live CoV calculator (Base, National bonus, Stackability bonus, Final score, Seal tier)LogRead-only audit trail
✓ DECISION: Log tab hides the footer action bar.
The Log tab is always read-only. The Submit/Cancel footer is hidden when Log is active.
✓ DECISION: Pending records are fully editable — not locked.
Opening the edit drawer on a pending record shows an amber notice but all fields remain live. Two actions are available:

Resubmit — supersedes the prior approval card, pushes a fresh one
Withdraw — cancels the pending card, reverts the record status, logs the withdrawal

✓ DECISION: Course Subject dropdown populates from the live course_subject ENUM in the Schema Manager.
If the enum values change in the Schema Manager, the dropdown reflects those changes immediately.
✓ DECISION: Reason for Change is required on every edit submission.
It appears in the approval card meta text so the Curriculum Director understands what changed and why.

